const myAnimal: Animal = "cat";

function foo(): string {
    return "Hello World!";
}
```

Here, we define a variable named myAnimal of type Animal, which can be one of the values "dog", "cat", or "bird". We then initialize myAnimal to be the string value "cat", which is of type Animal.

In the foo function, we use the typeof operator to specify that the return value will be a string. This means that any value returned by foo will be of type string, regardless of its actual value.

In summary, to specify the type of a variable or function in TypeScript, you can use the typeof operator and provide a list of possible values that match the type. By using types and typeof operators, you can ensure that your code is correct and follows a consistent set of rules.

